  "reasoning_summary": "Historically, extensive margin labor supply elasticities for single mothers in the US have been estimated to be relatively high (0.4 to 0.7), primarily based on EITC expansions in the 1980s and 1990s. Recent literature has challenged these findings, suggesting the elasticities could be much closer to zero once confounding welfare reforms and economic cycles are fully controlled for, which widens the subjective confidence interval downwards."
}
